@flexiarg war-machine/half-blind-observation
@title Half-Blind Observation

! conclusion: An observation surface that covers half the system produces worse decisions than no observation surface at all, because it creates false confidence in completeness.

  + CONTEXT:
    The evidence store initially scanned only part of the repo set, yet still produced plausible coverage statistics. Review exposed that missing channels and missing repos were being treated as invisible rather than as first-class uncertainty.

  + IF:
    The system is building an observation surface to drive recommendations, summaries, or prioritisation.

  + HOWEVER:
    Partial coverage is inevitable, but unacknowledged partial coverage is dangerous. A half-blind observer overweights what it can see and confidently ignores what it cannot.

  + THEN:
    Make every observation channel report both its findings and its coverage, and surface missing data as prominently as positive findings.

  + BECAUSE:
    An observer that knows it is blind can at least flag uncertainty. An observer that believes it sees everything makes confident wrong recommendations.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    next[Add explicit coverage reporting to every observation channel and refuse aggregate confidence claims that hide missing surfaces.]
